HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1567
By Lamberth
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend Teresa Keen on the
occasion of her retirement.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should specially
recognize those citizens who have performed with uncommon devotion and enthusiasm
throughout their years of public service; and
WHEREAS, Teresa Keen is one such estimable individual, who has rendered forty-nine
years of exceptional service to the City of Portland, serving through the tenures of eight different
mayors; and
WHEREAS, admired and respected for her knowledge, wisdom, and skill, Mrs. Keen has
served as the Assistant to the Mayor for the last four mayors of Portland, handling the good
times and the hard times equally with her steady diligence and dependability; and
WHEREAS, during her tenure as employee of the City of Portland, she has volunteered
with the Historical Society and with many other pivotal committees, always managing her role
with organizational skill and professionalism; and
WHEREAS, throughout her many years of service, she has enjoyed the love and
support of her husband, JC; and
WHEREAS, Teresa Keen exemplifies the spirit and allegiance to family and community
that are characteristic of a true Tennessean; and
WHEREAS, a woman of grace and integrity, Teresa Keen has compiled a singular
record of success during her exemplary public service career, and she should be specially
recognized; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
HJR1567
018524
- 1 -

CONCURRING, that we honor and commend Teresa Keen for her honorable and astute service
to the City of Portland and extend to her our best wishes for a happy and fulfilling retirement.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
